# i.lower.sdd

Scope: Latin lowercase i prototype glyph.

## Must

- Establish minimal lowercase stem logic for single-stroke glyphs.
- Keep stem width and x-height alignment compatible with `n.lower.sdd`.
- Define dot position as a spacing-aware visual anchor, not an afterthought.
- Clarify whether the dot remains a separate component or integrated stroke rhythm in a future phase.

## Must not

- Inflate body or dot width beyond its role as a narrow connector glyph.
- Let dot placement be copied blindly from existing roman defaults.
- Add descender-influenced treatment in a no-descender phase.

## Owns

- Lowercase single-stem vertical rhythm for `i/j` family in later phases.
- Dot placement and its spacing impact in short strings.
- Neutral entry/exit behavior for minimal-width combinations.

## Depends on

- `n.lower.sdd`
- `../../design-principles.sdd`
- `../../metrics/spacing.sdd`

## Forbids

- Dot touching the top of a body stem in any phase-internal setting.
- Overly rounded thin stems that visually weaken `nn` rhythm when paired with i.
- Manual micro-adjustments to compensate for absent prototype-level spacing rules.

## Done when

- i works in `ii`, `si`, `is`, `hi`, `ni`, and `ie` contexts in proof strings.
- Dot placement reads clearly at intended proof size without visual drift in repeated use (`iii`).
- Human review accepts dot policy as intentional and consistent for the phase.